00:16:08.421 --> 00:16:12.450
to create the dark elf race in the world and
by the way, that was a trip because after

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:17.200
I, when I finished the Halflings Gem, which
was the third book of that series. The fourth

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:22.620
book I had planned was going to send my heroes
back to recapture this dwarven homeland. And

00:16:22.620 --> 00:16:27.450
TSR, it was TSR back then, this was before
Wizards of the Coast called me up and said

00:16:27.450 --> 00:16:31.600
"You know we think people are sick of these
characters so just tie it up in this book

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:36.130
and we'll go do something else.' And that
was 1990; and we're still writing them so

00:16:36.130 --> 00:16:40.400
they were wrong and so I agreed and I tied
it up in that book. And then all of a sudden

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:44.370
I got a call "You know we're getting a lot
of letters about this dark elf guy, so maybe

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:48.720
we should do a series about where he came
from." And so I thought that would be great

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:53.450
and I had these old modules by Gary Gygax,
the Scent of the Depths of the Earth, you're

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:58.200
nodding, the classics the ones that followed
the Giant series. The Scent of the Depths

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:03.360
of the Earth, Queen of the Spider Web pits,
and you know and I, so I took the old modules

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:07.150
and they had all this information about dark
elves, just a little bit here and there. And

00:17:07.150 --> 00:17:12.600
the theme folio, one of the first edition
monster books had just come out and they had

00:17:12.600 --> 00:17:17.620
like a one page entry on dark elves. And so
I had all of that, I gathered all of that

00:17:17.620 --> 00:17:21.370
and I'm reading it and I'm like "Oo that's
not a lot" So I called up to TSR and said

00:17:21.370 --> 00:17:25.400
"ok I've got all these things, what else are
you going to send me?" And they said "That's

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:29.820
all there is" I said "Wait a minute what are
you talking about?" And they said "Oh no,

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:34.290
we're giving you carte blanche you're going
to created the dark elves in the forgotten

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:44.350
realms" I go "Ok" so I went and I got out
one of my favorite books of all time the Godfather,

00:17:44.350 --> 00:17:51.490
Mario Puzo's The Godfather. And that is the,
that is basis for the structure of the dark

00:17:51.490 --> 00:18:00.559
elvin city. Well that and the fact that I
have five older sisters. [Laughter] They always

00:18:00.559 --> 00:18:07.309
come up to me and say "I'm the good one, right?"
There really isn't any good one. But yeah,

00:18:07.309 --> 00:18:12.040
that's and that's where it came from. But
I spent so much time hiding. And it always,

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.669
we always get in trouble when they pull me
out, because when I was doing the Thousand

00:18:15.669 --> 00:18:20.140
Orcs, they say "You know, you're hiding too
much, but we need you to do more with the

00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:27.250
realms. So you know, can you use some characters
from the campaign setting." And so I'm looking

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:31.140
through and I'm finding characters that fit
like King Obould - Many Arrows of the Orcs.

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:35.570
And I'm like "Oh this is cool can I use?"
"Yeah yeah yeah" "Well look I'm warning you

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:43.280
if I use him, I can kill him" "Yeah, of course,
of course, no problem" So I write the book

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:49.120
and I send it in and my editors like "Bob
we got a problem" "Well what's the problem"

00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:54.490
"Well on the timeline, your book is actually
set before the campaign setting, so you can't

00:18:54.490 --> 00:18:58.179
kill him" Like "Wait a minute!" This always
happens because you have so many hands in

00:18:58.179 --> 00:19:04.540
this giant pot, you know. And with Neverwinter
I was, I was happy, I'm always happy to play

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:10.059
with others in this sandbox, as long as it's
not going to hinder on what I wanted to do.

00:19:10.059 --> 00:19:14.740
I have a reason for writing all of these books.
There's something that I want to explore.

00:19:14.740 --> 00:19:20.720
And with the new books, Gontal, Grim through
the book that's coming in March. For most

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:28.321
of the books, my main character is surrounded
by people of similar wheel, right? Anyone

00:19:28.321 --> 00:19:32.929
of that group, Cattie-Brie, Bruenor, Regis,
Wulfgar and Drizzt, anyone one of them would

00:19:32.929 --> 00:19:38.160
take an arrow that was aimed for somebody
else. And now here's my main character and

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:43.950
he's alone, he's depressed, the world's gone
dark, it's all cynicism, he's wondering if

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:50.540
his whole life and his entire moral code was
nothing but a sad joke after all. And now

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:54.410
he's surrounded by people who not only wouldn't
take the arrow aimed for him but would pull

00:19:54.410 --> 00:19:59.480
him in front of them to block the arrow. So,
it's like the kid you know in high school

00:19:59.480 --> 00:20:02.940
who falls in with the wrong crowd, or if you
have a friend, who starts dating someone and

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:06.260
they're getting serious and you know this
persons really bad for him but there's nothing

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:10.120
you can do about it. And you can only hope
that they're going to lift this person up

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:15.280
instead of getting dragged down, right? And
that's what, that was the story of the Neverwinter

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.200
saga. And then they just said, "So for the
icing on the cake, can you blow up a city?"

00:20:20.200 --> 00:20:26.570
Yep. "Can you add some characters to the city?"
Yep, I can do that. And when it works like

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:29.780
that, it's awesome, shared world is awesome.
Because you are standing on the shoulders

00:20:29.780 --> 00:20:35.280
of giants. Best example of that I'm writing
Streams of Silver the second book. And I've

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:41.450
got to get from Icewind Dale go about a quarter
way across the world to the Silver marches.

00:20:41.450 --> 00:20:44.950
And I'm trying to figure out what I'm going
to do. You know, when you're doing a travel

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:50.110
book, it's hard to, you know, have a random
encounter table, like you do in the games.

00:20:50.110 --> 00:20:53.950
So it's hard to make it interesting. And there
was this one town along the way called Long

00:20:53.950 --> 00:21:00.240
Saddle. And so I looked in my grey box at,
my 25-year-old Forgotten Realms box set and

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:07.350
this was 24 years ago, so, and they talk about
this town and all it said was that Long Saddle

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:11.740
is ruled by a family of eccentric wizards
who reside in the Ivy Mansion. That's like

00:21:11.740 --> 00:21:18.490
all it said. So, now the wheels start turning,
how can I make this fun? And so I come up

00:21:18.490 --> 00:21:24.360
with the Harples I think it said the Harples.
But I came up with the main the actual characters

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:29.650
and I started having them do really goofy
things, like the wizards house was surrounded

00:21:29.650 --> 00:21:34.360
by an invisible wall and so everyday someone
would have to come up and scrape the birds

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:41.000
off it. Right? And one guy turned, he had
this brilliant spell that would turn him into

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.870
a statue and he had another spell to take
them out without realizing that once he turned

00:21:45.870 --> 00:21:50.960
into a statue he couldn't do the other spell.
So he's standing there. And they had a bridge

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:55.350
that you don't walk over you walk under, right?
It's all these weird stupid things and it

00:21:55.350 --> 00:21:59.080
was so much fun. And I called Ed Greenwood
and Ed Greenwood was the guy who created the

00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:04.970
Forgotten Realms when he was eight years old
and that's true. And I said "Ed, I want to

00:22:04.970 --> 00:22:09.380
read you what I have about Long Saddle, what
do you think?" And we just had the best time

00:22:09.380 --> 00:22:13.980
going back and forth about that. That's when
shared world works and it is so much fun.

00:22:13.980 --> 00:22:17.390
&gt;&gt; Male 3: I'm really curious about the writing
process, I'm not a writer I've never been

00:22:17.390 --> 00:22:22.070
a writer, my dad taught English in high school.
Ah, but I always wanted to write and never

00:22:22.070 --> 00:22:26.010
been able to. But I'm curious about how you
actually go about writing, it sounds like

00:22:26.010 --> 00:22:30.750
you're much more structured about how you
approach the story, you sort of figure out

00:22:30.750 --> 00:22:36.070
the the arcs and the small arcs and you fill
in the details. Whereas like, for example,

00:22:36.070 --> 00:22:39.450
Terry Pratchett I've heard talk and he said
he just goes into his office and writes 500

00:22:39.450 --> 00:22:43.950
words a day, like boom boom everyday and just
comes up, the story just emerges. It sounds

00:22:43.950 --> 00:22:48.039
like you are much more structured.
&gt;&gt; Bob: I fooled you. Hah hah. Here's what

00:22:48.039 --> 00:22:54.520
I do, I have to an outline for a few reasons,
whether I'm doing a shared world or my own

00:22:54.520 --> 00:23:00.190
books, I have a lot of books in my own world,
so I can blow up everything, right? And I

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:03.180
have to do an outline, the publishers demand
an outline, because they want to know, you

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:07.730
are actually thinking about it and working.
So I write my outline and I send it in, because

00:23:07.730 --> 00:23:14.040
I want to get paid and then I start writing
and I throw the outline away. And the characters,

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:21.620
the characters tell me what's next. And I
often don't know, I am often shocked at things

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:28.510
that happen in the books. They surprise me
all the time. You know, oops I accidentally

00:23:28.510 --> 00:23:35.900
just killed that person, oh, wait a minute,
you know. This is the way it works and I think,

00:23:35.900 --> 00:23:40.610
I think I write the books the way other people
read books. And that's what makes it fun for

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:47.580
me, without that it'd be boring. Now there
are times that it doesn't work like that.

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:55.169
Star Wars, you have to tell them exactly what
you're going to do in Star Wars and I remember

00:23:55.169 --> 00:24:02.100
when I signed on to do Vector Prime, the infamous
one, you know I wrote the outline and I sent

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:10.030
it in and I'm in a conference call with Lucas
Film in Del Ray. And, you know, "Aw, this

00:24:10.030 --> 00:24:13.570
is great, this is exactly what we want." They
had told me the overview of this new Jedi

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:19.300
order, like A to Z and I was supposed to to
A to B or A to C and I had certain things,

00:24:19.300 --> 00:24:23.960
beat points that I had to hit and I had to
leave everything in a certain way. I just

00:24:23.960 --> 00:24:28.010
had to come up with a story that made it through
those beat points. And they go "This is great,

00:24:28.010 --> 00:24:32.880
this is exactly what we wanted, but didn't
anyone tell you?" I said "what?" "You have

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:38.670
to kill Chewbacca" and I was like, next words
that came out of my mouth I'm never going

00:24:38.670 --> 00:24:47.809
to say on camera, but it wasn't nice. Oh no
this is from on high, the Wookie gets it.

00:24:47.809 --> 00:24:57.380
And So that was much more structured, working
in Star Wars, but no, I, they tell me. That's

00:24:57.380 --> 00:25:01.640
what makes it fun.
