&gt;&gt; Male 1: Another question about writing,

00:30:05.950 --> 00:30:09.669
particularly your mention of the new multi
media setup, how do you see that a

00:30:09.669 --> 00:30:13.590
effecting newer authors, like if you're established
and have the publishing company relations

00:30:13.590 --> 00:30:18.440
and can sort of pull rank it works very well
I'm sure and has for you, but if you're newer

00:30:18.440 --> 00:30:22.840
now and trying come on to the scene in sci-fi
fantasy how does it work with the newer market

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:25.039
world?
&gt;&gt; Bob: I probably don't have a good answer

00:30:25.039 --> 00:30:30.340
for this, but I'll tell you what I've learned.
You know, now that it's so cheap to self publish,

00:30:30.340 --> 00:30:35.950
a lot of people are doing it, that's good
and bad. What's good about it is a lot of

00:30:35.950 --> 00:30:40.480
people who were never going to get a chance
can do it and they can get their book out

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:45.240
there and you can even print, you know, back
when I started, if you were going to print

00:30:45.240 --> 00:30:52.520
a book, you had to print 10,000, the costs
were just so unreal, if you were under that

00:30:52.520 --> 00:30:58.070
number of the print run. But now they change
those big web presses, they change right on

00:30:58.070 --> 00:31:02.779
the fly you know, I need 73 of this book,
boom, I need 15 of that book, boom and it

00:31:02.779 --> 00:31:08.430
just completely just switches over automatically.
Before that, they had to shut everything down,

00:31:08.430 --> 00:31:12.799
you know, put the new plates in and everything,
so it wasn't worth it. Now you can go and

00:31:12.799 --> 00:31:19.020
print on demand at you know minimal cost and
plus you have eBooks, where you can sell them.

00:31:19.020 --> 00:31:26.890
The problem, however, is that instead of having,
you know 50 or 60,000 books a year being printed

00:31:26.890 --> 00:31:37.190
in the US, with self publishing you have 200,000
and that means that, the, you know any prospective

00:31:37.190 --> 00:31:43.720
readers, how are they going to find you, over
the noise of everybody else? So there are

00:31:43.720 --> 00:31:48.090
people, you've, I'm sure most of you have
heard of Chris Paolini he wrote the Eragon

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:53.990
books and he was self published, his parents
self published him. And they would take him

00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:58.809
all around the Northwest and go to like junior
high schools and stuff to give talks and he'd

00:31:58.809 --> 00:32:04.090
be in costume from Eragon. When, he was like
20 at the time. And they would go all around

00:32:04.090 --> 00:32:10.460
with the book and through that he found a
publisher, so a lot of people now, it is so

00:32:10.460 --> 00:32:16.720
hard to go to a publisher because the book
industry with all the changes is in such flux,

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:21.890
you know, the margins are razor thin, so it's
so hard for a new author to find a publisher

00:32:21.890 --> 00:32:27.880
now. A lot of them will self publish, try
to build some kind of a following then try

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:34.580
to go the traditional route with that. I don't
know how it's working for most, I do have

00:32:34.580 --> 00:32:40.010
several friends, several of the guys at 38
Studios actually I edited books for them and

00:32:40.010 --> 00:32:46.640
then they they put them out there on eBook
format. So it's better because you can be

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:53.450
