coolest monster in the game and I don't want
to ruin it, what's the matter with you?" but

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:55.519
every DM hated me for years on end. So every
now and then, something will break out, but

00:49:55.519 --> 00:50:01.839
you know, being different just for the sake
of being different can get you really no where.

00:50:01.839 --> 00:50:06.119
So, I don't think, I don't think it's a big
deal.

00:50:06.119 --> 00:50:08.759
&gt;&gt; Male 1: Thank you.
&gt;&gt; Bob: You're welcome.

00:50:08.759 --> 00:50:13.569
&gt;&gt; Announcer: I think we have the time for
one final question. I was personally wondering

00:50:13.569 --> 00:50:18.469
how you keep track of continuity in cannon
especially among, you know, your series of

00:50:18.469 --> 00:50:23.259
books and then as you said playing in other
peoples worlds. How do you make sure that

00:50:23.259 --> 00:50:27.660
everything is described properly and get those
allusions that harken back?

00:50:27.660 --> 00:50:35.339
&gt;&gt; Bob: I don't. No, I'm only kidding. it's
hard. I mean, people come up to me and they

00:50:35.339 --> 00:50:40.799
start talking about like Streams of Silver,
right? And they start "Aw that part in this

00:50:40.799 --> 00:50:46.219
book when this happened" and I nod stupidly
and pretend I know what they're talking about.

00:50:46.219 --> 00:50:52.270
I wrote that book in 1988. I've done, you
know, 30 books since. I don't re-read them

00:50:52.270 --> 00:50:59.180
every year. But you know, we do have a wiki,
the wiki is saving me. I'll go to Google,

00:50:59.180 --> 00:51:10.209
I go to Google and I say, you know "Brunner,
scar" and the search comes up and brings me

00:51:10.209 --> 00:51:15.869
to a page that'll tell me where Brunner's
scar is and how he got it and when it happened.

00:51:15.869 --> 00:51:20.130
And so it's like the entire fan base is doing
your research for you and they're putting

00:51:20.130 --> 00:51:24.890
it up on all these little forgotten realms
wiki all over the place. And this is a true

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:29.829
story, many years ago I was writing a book
called Servant of the Shard and what I thought

00:51:29.829 --> 00:51:34.619
was really cool is I have this character who
was just a lark, his name is Jarlaxle. And

00:51:34.619 --> 00:51:40.160
Jarlaxle is a, if you are familiar with the
literally term deus ex machina, right? A good

00:51:40.160 --> 00:51:45.059
example of deus ex machina the dragon shows
up, it's killing everybody in the town; I've

00:51:45.059 --> 00:51:48.900
got a better one, actually, War of the Worlds,
right? The Martians show up, they're throwing

00:51:48.900 --> 00:51:53.910
everything at them, they can't do anything
and then all of a sudden they all die of colds,

00:51:53.910 --> 00:52:00.319
right? The common cold wipes out the Martians.
Or the dragons ravaging the town and nothing

00:52:00.319 --> 00:52:04.789
can stop it and our hero falls down against
a rock, the rock moves and he finds a sword

00:52:04.789 --> 00:52:08.605
that was crafted by the elves 3000 years ago
to kill that dragon. So he stabs the dragon

00:52:08.605 --> 00:52:14.150
and it dies. So that's deus ex machina the
gods intervene essentially. Jarlaxle is my

00:52:14.150 --> 00:52:18.549
walking deus ex machina and he would show
up in cameos in the books and no matter what

00:52:18.549 --> 00:52:23.759
was going on he had his little Jarlaxle Batman
utility belt and he had something, some weird

00:52:23.759 --> 00:52:28.410
magic item to counteract what was bad, what
bad was about to happen. It was a blast to

00:52:28.410 --> 00:52:32.969
write. But he showed up in all weird places
in the books, the first books of the series

00:52:32.969 --> 00:52:37.560
and now I'm psyched because he's going to
be a main character in this book. And then

00:52:37.560 --> 00:52:42.859
I'm terrified, because I've only got four
months to write the book and I have no idea

00:52:42.859 --> 00:52:47.990
what this guy has for equipment. And I'm looking
at this pile of my previous books and I'm

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:54.829
like "Oh no, you know, where, which books
was he in, where am I going to find this stuff?"

00:52:54.829 --> 00:53:02.559
And, so I was about to call TSR and ask for
an extension, but instead I went online to

00:53:02.559 --> 00:53:08.630
a message board anonymously, right? And I
started a thread that said "Hey lets do an

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:15.529
inventory of Jarlaxle's cool items" and two
days later I went back and I downloaded this

00:53:15.529 --> 00:53:22.469
like ten page thread. And they were putting
in like, it was all footnoted, you know, in

00:53:22.469 --> 00:53:28.900
legacy, in the Legacy, page 227, they talk
about this item that Jarlaxle has and it does

00:53:28.900 --> 00:53:33.209
this and I think it's hinted it might do.
So I grab the Legacy and I go to the page

00:53:33.209 --> 00:53:39.979
and "Yeah, there it is" And there it was,
that's how I kept continuity. other than that,

00:53:39.979 --> 00:53:45.910
it's up to, that's like some poor soul at
Wizards of the Coast gets assigned or at Lucas

00:53:45.910 --> 00:53:51.789
Film they hire some guy and say "You are the
continuity editor" "Oh you know I've got this

00:53:51.789 --> 00:53:57.630
great job" And then four truck loads of stuff
back ups to his house and dumps stacks of

00:53:57.630 --> 00:54:03.620
books and DVDs and everything else on his
front porch and it's like "Here's the new

00:54:03.620 --> 00:54:08.660
book check it for continuity". And he's got
this mountain of stuff, this poor guy. But

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:15.269
they, so it can get problematic and of course
the real secret to doing long term in the

00:54:15.269 --> 00:54:20.309
shared world is being able to retrofit things
seamlessly and make it look like you planned

00:54:20.309 --> 00:54:29.150
it all along. We cheat, not often, but because
we try hard to keep things straight. So, we'd

00:54:29.150 --> 00:54:34.029
start anonymous threads on message boards.
&gt;&gt; Announcer: Alright well thank you very

00:54:34.029 --> 00:54:36.869
much, we'll have a book signing in the back
so thanks for speaking at Google.

00:54:36.869 --> 00:54:37.979
&gt;&gt; Bob: Thanks for having me here!
[Applause]

